<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="heuristic-evaluation">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-ui-designer</domain>
    <summary>3-5 evaluators independently review interface against Nielsen's 10 heuristics, rate issues on 0-4 severity scale. Catches ~75% of violations at near-zero cost.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>usability-testing</tag>
      <tag>heuristic-evaluation</tag>
      <tag>expert-review</tag>
      <tag>quality-assurance</tag>
      <tag>severit-scale</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Heuristic Evaluation</title>

    <summary>A structured usability inspection method where 3-5 evaluators independently review an interface against Nielsen's 10 heuristics and rate each issue on a 0-4 severity scale (0=not a problem, 4=catastrophic). Evaluators work independently first, then findings are compiled and deduplicated. One pass per heuristic yields ~3x more findings than a single omnibus pass. Severity 4 blocks release; severity 3 is sprint-level; severity 1-2 goes to polish backlog.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Full usability testing is expensive and time-consuming. Heuristic evaluation finds obvious violations at near-zero cost — 3-5 evaluators catch ~75% of issues vs ~35% for one evaluator. Expert review before user testing ensures test sessions surface real user struggles, not violations any UX professional would catch. The method also serves as a forcing function for design documentation: evaluators need to know intended behavior to judge violations.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Before a usability test — eliminate obvious violations so testing resources address real user behavior</item>
        <item>When no user research budget is available — gives actionable findings at near-zero cost</item>
        <item>After a design sprint or major redesign — rapid expert review before development handoff</item>
        <item>Code review for UI components — catching violations in PRs prevents regressions</item>
        <item>Competitive analysis: apply the same heuristics to competitors to score relative quality</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>As a replacement for usability testing — finds expert-visible violations, not real user struggles with domain tasks</item>
        <item>After launch as the sole quality gate — too late for design changes; use for iterative improvements</item>
        <item>When quantitative data is needed to justify decisions — heuristic evaluation produces qualitative expert opinions</item>
        <item>On expert-user products where violations are worked around via muscle memory — disrupting their efficiency is worse</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="nielsens-10-heuristics">
      <p>The canonical heuristic set against which evaluators assess an interface. Each heuristic is a usability principle, not a detailed checklist.</p>
      <list>
        <item>#1 Visibility of system status — does the user always know what is happening?</item>
        <item>#2 Match between system and real world — does it use user language?</item>
        <item>#3 User control and freedom — can the user undo and exit?</item>
        <item>#4 Consistency and standards — is behavior predictable?</item>
        <item>#5 Error prevention — does it prevent mistakes before they happen?</item>
        <item>#6 Recognition over recall — are options visible rather than remembered?</item>
        <item>#7 Flexibility and efficiency of use — does it support expert shortcuts?</item>
        <item>#8 Aesthetic and minimalist design — is the interface clutter-free?</item>
        <item>#9 Help users recognize, diagnose, and recover from errors — are errors helpful?</item>
        <item>#10 Help and documentation — is help available when needed?</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="evaluator-requirements">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use 3-5 evaluators. Each evaluator works independently before any group discussion. Combining findings happens only after all individual evaluations are complete.</statement>
        <rationale>3-5 evaluators find ~75% of usability issues; a single evaluator finds ~35%. Independent evaluation prevents anchoring bias — if evaluators discuss first, later evaluators' findings are biased toward earlier findings. Independence maximizes coverage.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Run one heuristic per evaluation pass. Do not attempt to evaluate all 10 heuristics simultaneously in one walkthrough.</statement>
        <rationale>Single-heuristic focus produces 3x more findings per heuristic than omnibus evaluation. Evaluating all 10 at once produces shallow coverage of each. Dedicated passes allow deeper attention and catch issues missed by divided attention.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="severity-scale">
      <rule>
        <statement>Rate every finding on a 0-4 severity scale. Use this scale consistently for prioritization: severity 4 blocks release, severity 3 is a sprint-level fix, severity 1-2 goes to the polish backlog.</statement>
        <rationale>Without consistent severity ratings, all issues appear equally urgent and teams cannot prioritize. The 0-4 scale (from Nielsen 1994) provides a shared vocabulary for comparing findings across evaluators and cycles.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>0: Not a usability problem</item>
        <item>1: Cosmetic — fix only if extra time available</item>
        <item>2: Minor — low priority, should fix</item>
        <item>3: Major — important to fix, high priority</item>
        <item>4: Catastrophic — imperative to fix before release</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="six-step-process">
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 1: Define scope — which screens/flows to evaluate, which heuristics to focus on, which task scenarios to walk through.</statement>
        <rationale>Undefined scope leads to surface-level review. Task scenarios anchor evaluation to realistic usage rather than abstract interface inspection.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 2: Gather materials — interface or prototype access, task scenarios, evaluation template, screen recording if possible.</statement>
        <rationale>Consistent materials across evaluators ensure comparable findings. Screen recordings allow revisiting observations during compilation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Steps 3-4: Each evaluator independently walks through the interface against each heuristic, documents findings with location, heuristic, problem description, severity, and recommendation. Then compile: remove duplicates, aggregate severity ratings (average where they differ, note range).</statement>
        <rationale>Compilation after independent evaluation preserves diversity of findings while removing noise. Averaging severity ratings across evaluators reduces individual bias.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 6: Report findings with concrete location references (screen name, component, flow step) and specific recommendations. "UI is confusing" is not an actionable finding.</statement>
        <rationale>Vague findings cannot be acted on. A finding without a location cannot be reproduced. A finding without a recommendation leaves remediation to chance. All three elements are required for each finding to be actionable.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="example-findings">
      <example type="good" title="Well-formed finding — checkout page, heuristic #5, severity 3">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Location:       Checkout page → Payment form → Card number field
Heuristic:      #5 Error Prevention
Problem:        No validation for credit card number format.
                Users can enter letters and invalid numbers without
                warning until form submission — causing a full-page
                error after they have entered all other fields.
Severity:       3 (Major)
Recommendation: Add real-time format validation. Show checkmarks
                as user enters valid card number sections.
                Auto-detect card type from first 4 digits.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Finding with clear before/after recommendation">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Location:       Settings → Account → Delete Account
Heuristic:      #3 User Control and Freedom
Problem:        "Delete Account" button immediately deletes without
                confirmation. Action is irreversible. No undo.
Severity:       4 (Catastrophic)
Recommendation: Add confirmation dialog requiring the user to
                type their email address to confirm deletion.
                Show consequences ("Your data will be permanently
                deleted in 30 days") with a cancel window.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="severity-rating-reference">
      <list>
        <item>0: "The icon on the settings page is slightly outdated but universally recognized" — preference, not a usability issue</item>
        <item>1: "Help link in footer uses the same color as body text, making it less visible" — cosmetic, not task-blocking</item>
        <item>2: "Help documentation link is buried 3 menu levels deep" — minor, users can find it with effort</item>
        <item>3: "Cannot complete checkout without discovering the non-obvious 'Continue' button" — major, causes significant failure rate</item>
        <item>4: "Critical function 'Submit Order' is broken on mobile Safari" — catastrophic, blocks core task</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Evaluators collaborating or discussing before individual evaluations are complete</description>
        <reason>Early discussion anchors all evaluators to the first person's findings. Later evaluators fail to explore areas already covered and underweight areas not mentioned. Independent evaluation is the core quality mechanism of the method.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Vague findings: "The UI is confusing" or "Navigation is hard to use"</description>
        <reason>Cannot be reproduced, prioritized, or actioned. Minimum valid finding: location + heuristic + specific problem + severity + recommendation. All five fields are required.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Single evaluator evaluation presented as comprehensive</description>
        <reason>One evaluator finds ~35% of issues. Claiming comprehensive coverage from a single-evaluator review sets false expectations. Always note evaluator count in the report methodology section.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent declaring "no violations found" for a heuristic without explicit reasoning</description>
        <reason>Either the interface is genuinely excellent for that heuristic, or the evaluator did not look thoroughly. A "no violations" declaration requires a brief explanation of why the heuristic is satisfied, not just absence of findings.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="heuristic-evaluation-vs-usability-testing">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use heuristic evaluation to find expert-detectable violations before usability testing. Use usability testing to find real-user struggles that only emerge from domain-specific tasks and actual usage behavior.</statement>
        <rationale>The two methods are complementary, not substitutes. Heuristic evaluation is faster and cheaper but finds violations, not user behavior. Usability testing with real users finds struggles that expert evaluators miss because they know the system too well. Run both for complete coverage.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="where-heuristic-evaluation-fails">
      <p>Single-evaluator heuristic review finds only ~35% of issues; 3-5 evaluators finds ~75% — agents acting as a single evaluator have the same coverage limitation. Heuristic evaluation has evaluator bias: what an agent classifies as "major" may be "cosmetic" to real users or vice versa. Domain-specific mental models are hard to encode — an agent evaluating a medical device UI without clinical workflow knowledge will miss violations that matter most. The method produces a list of problems, not solutions — recommendation quality depends on evaluator experience, which agents simulate but do not possess. Inter-rater reliability is low even among human experts; agent severity ratings should be treated as first-pass triage, not final scores.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>An agent can serve as a structured heuristic evaluator for digital interfaces — given access to screenshots, HTML/JSX, or design file exports, it can systematically apply Nielsen's 10 heuristics, log violations with location and severity, and produce a compiled report. Running the agent multiple times with different focus heuristics (one pass per heuristic) improves coverage better than a single omnibus pass. Human review of severity ratings and final prioritization is the required checkpoint — agents overrate cosmetic issues and underrate domain-specific violations.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>An agent evaluating the same interface multiple times with the same prompt tends to reproduce the same findings</description>
        <reason>Vary the user scenario and focus heuristic to increase coverage</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents inflate severity ratings for visually prominent issues and underrate violations in less conspicuous locations</description>
        <reason>Severity calibration requires human judgment</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Heuristic #8 (aesthetic and minimalist design) is the most subjective; agent ratings for "excessive visual noise" depend heavily on training examples</description>
        <reason>Be explicit about design philosophy in prompts; validate ratings with domain experts</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents cannot evaluate heuristic #7 (flexibility and efficiency of use) for keyboard shortcuts and power-user features without interacting with the product</description>
        <reason>Supplement agent evaluation with interactive testing for keyboard-dependent workflows</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent declaring "no violations found" for a heuristic without explanation</description>
        <reason>Either the interface is genuinely excellent or the agent did not look hard enough; always ask for explicit reasoning per heuristic</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Run one heuristic per evaluation pass — single omnibus pass produces shallow findings; dedicated passes catch ~3x more issues per heuristic</item>
        <item>Severity 4 items block release; severity 3 items are sprint-level fixes; severity 1-2 items go into polish backlog — use this triage consistently</item>
        <item>Provide concrete location references (screen name, element name, user flow step) — "UI is confusing" is not actionable</item>
        <item>Run evaluations against the same task scenarios your user research uses — enables direct comparison with usability test findings</item>
        <item>Use heuristic evaluation as a forcing function for design documentation — evaluators need to understand intended behavior; gaps reveal missing specs</item>
        <item>Document what was evaluated (specific screens, flows, prototype version, date) — without this, findings cannot be reproduced or compared later</item>
        <item>Combine with automated tools: axe-core covers ~30% of violations detectable programmatically, freeing evaluators to focus on judgment-heavy heuristics (#2, #6, #8)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/evaluation-form.md" purpose="Per-evaluator form: scope, findings (location/heuristic/problem/severity/recommendation), summary table"/>
      <template path="templates/compiled-report.md" purpose="Compiled report: executive summary, methodology, findings by severity (4→1), findings by heuristic, statistics, recommendations"/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/ten-usability-heuristics/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
